Diastematomelia presenting in adult life has long been considered a rare 
occurrence. With the development of modern imagining techniques, cases of adult 
are being discovered with increasing frequency, but their exact number remains 
unclear. It occurs most often in the lumbar region, is rarely located above the 
level of T3 and it present clinical features such as deformity of the food, 
peculiar posture, or gait disturbance. The symptoms and signs of diastematomelia 
usually are recognized in children. We are reporting the case of an adult 
